01:02:33,503 --> 01:02:36,682
I know, Walter.
It doesn't make any sense at all.

913
01:02:36,788 --> 01:02:42,213
- Thank God my life is in place.
- Duluth? That's in North Dakota.

914
01:02:56,944 --> 01:02:59,904
I love this letter.
You have to write to her.

915
01:03:00,072 --> 01:03:01,862
You think so?

916
01:03:02,032 --> 01:03:05,622
It's Y-O-H.
Yeah. What's that?

917
01:03:05,786 --> 01:03:07,536
Your only hope.

918
01:03:19,256 --> 01:03:23,579
I thought I would look into doing
a story on those radio shows.

919
01:03:24,477 --> 01:03:27,055
You probably will have to go
somewhere to really look into them.

920
01:03:27,249 --> 01:03:28,945
Definitely.

921
01:03:48,368 --> 01:03:52,461
- Couldn't you do a phone interview?
- Not for the kind of piece I wanna do.

922
01:03:52,662 --> 01:03:57,016
- I won't be in Chicago for that long.
- When you get back, I'll be gone.

923
01:03:57,244 --> 01:04:01,374
- Then I'll see you in New York.
- Okay, I'll get it.

924
01:04:05,614 --> 01:04:10,548
<i>This is Captain Browning.
We're about cruising at 35,000 feet.</i>

925
01:04:10,657 --> 01:04:16,127
<i>The weather is clear to the west and we
expect arrival in Seattle on schedule.</i>

926
01:04:16,381 --> 01:04:18,381
Don't you hate flying?

927
01:04:18,501 --> 01:04:23,883
Yes, I do. And I've just told the most
terrible one to the man I'm about to marry.

928
01:04:24,305 --> 01:04:27,110
Do you feel that any
lie is a betrayal?

929
01:04:28,081 --> 01:04:31,921
- I said flying.
- Ooh...

930
01:04:38,258 --> 01:04:41,851
- Thanks for bringing me here.
- Well, he likes the planes.

931
01:04:42,640 --> 01:04:45,164
Can I bring something back for you?
A souvenir?

932
01:04:45,292 --> 01:04:47,042
Does he like those
little snow globes?

933
01:04:47,128 --> 01:04:49,633
You know, you shake them up
and then the snow floats down.

934
01:04:49,729 --> 01:04:53,221
Sure, I'd really like that.
Thank you so much.

935
01:04:57,475 --> 01:04:59,935
- He's 8.
- He's good at it.

936
01:05:00,131 --> 01:05:03,717
I've read an article about this.
Children are hideous at the age of 8.

937
01:05:03,811 --> 01:05:05,459
- It's quite normal.
- Well...

938
01:05:06,201 --> 01:05:10,412
Maybe when I come back, the two of us ought
to spend some time together on our own.

939
01:05:10,617 --> 01:05:12,311
What do you think?

940
01:05:16,536 --> 01:05:19,051
Bye.
Bye, Jonah.

941
01:05:19,260 --> 01:05:20,231
Bye.

942
01:05:24,864 --> 01:05:25,957
Jonah.

943
01:05:27,054 --> 01:05:31,066
Listen to me.
You don't know Victoria.

944
01:05:31,254 --> 01:05:35,968
I hardly know her myself.
She's, in fact, a mystery to me.

945
01:05:36,232 --> 01:05:39,132
She tosses her hair a lot.
Why does she do this?

946
01:05:39,351 --> 01:05:42,546
I have no idea. Is it a twitch?
Does she need a haircut?

947
01:05:42,571 --> 01:05:45,647
Could she use a barrette
to keep her hair out of her face?

948
01:05:47,021 --> 01:05:49,903
These are the things I'm
willing to get to the bottom of.

949
01:05:50,402 --> 01:05:54,532
That is why I am dating her.

950
01:05:54,698 --> 01:06:00,162
That's all I'm doing. I'm not living
with her. I'm not marrying her.

951
01:06:00,261 --> 01:06:02,694
Can you appreciate the difference?

952
01:06:03,770 --> 01:06:08,167
This is what single people do. They try
other people on and see how they fit.

953
01:06:08,277 --> 01:06:11,496
But everybody's an adjustment.
Nobody's perfect.

954
01:06:11,909 --> 01:06:14,433
There's no such thing
as a perfect...

955
01:06:30,629 --> 01:06:31,668
Come on.

956
01:06:34,821 --> 01:06:38,031
Dad, I was talking to
Jessica about reincarnation.

957
01:06:38,199 --> 01:06:40,582
She says you knew Annie
in another life.

958
01:06:40,699 --> 01:06:42,816
- Who's Annie?
- The one who wrote us.

959
01:06:42,917 --> 01:06:46,580
But Jessica says, you and Annie
never got together in that life.

960
01:06:46,605 --> 01:06:49,271
So your hearts are like
puzzles with missing pieces.

961
01:06:49,296 --> 01:06:51,685
And when you get together,
the puzzle's complete.

962
01:06:51,748 --> 01:06:52,904
Goddamn it.

963
01:06:53,123 --> 01:06:54,709
The reason I know this
and you don't,

964
01:06:54,798 --> 01:06:59,218
is because I'm younger and pure, so
I'm more in touch with cosmic forces.

965
01:06:59,417 --> 01:07:01,000
Who told you this stuff?

966
01:07:01,025 --> 01:07:02,133
Jessica.

967
01:07:02,253 --> 01:07:05,446
I sincerely hope you're
not marrying Jessica.

968
01:07:11,497 --> 01:07:15,911
<i>♪ I remember the days
of just keeping time ♪</i>

969
01:07:16,167 --> 01:07:22,363
<i>♪ Of hanging around
In sleepy towns forever ♪</i>

970
01:07:22,700 --> 01:07:26,426
<i>♪ Back roads empty for miles ♪</i>

971
01:07:28,474 --> 01:07:33,074
<i>♪ Well, you can't have a dream
And cut it to fit ♪</i>

972
01:07:33,353 --> 01:07:36,575
<i>♪ But when I saw you, I knew ♪</i>

973
01:07:37,079 --> 01:07:43,098
<i>♪ We'd go together
Like a wink and a smile ♪</i>

974
01:07:46,577 --> 01:07:50,308
<i>♪ Leave your old jalopy ♪</i>

975
01:07:50,542 --> 01:07:54,457
<i>♪ By the railroad track ♪</i>

976
01:07:54,845 --> 01:07:59,174
<i>♪ We'll get a hip double-dip tip-toppy ♪</i>

977
01:07:59,285 --> 01:08:02,885
<i>♪ Two-seat Pontiac ♪</i>

978
01:08:04,885 --> 01:08:09,643
<i>♪ So you can rev her up
Don't go slow ♪</i>

979
01:08:09,763 --> 01:08:13,325
<i>♪ It's only green lights and all rights ♪</i>

980
01:08:13,449 --> 01:08:20,153
<i>♪ Let's go together
With a wink and a smile ♪</i>

981
01:08:33,811 --> 01:08:37,623
<i>♪ Give me a wink and a smile ♪</i>

982
01:08:48,783 --> 01:08:54,384
<i>♪ We go together
Like a wink and a smile ♪</i>

983
01:08:57,375 --> 01:09:00,970
<i>♪ Now my heart is music ♪</i>

984
01:09:01,047 --> 01:09:04,368
<i>♪ Such a simple song ♪</i>

985
01:09:05,276 --> 01:09:09,533
<i>♪ Sing it again
The notes never end ♪</i>

986
01:09:09,652 --> 01:09:13,517
<i>♪ This is where I belong ♪</i>

987
01:09:13,614 --> 01:09:15,962
<i>♪ Just the sound of your voice ♪</i>

988
01:09:16,048 --> 01:09:18,103
<i>♪ The light in your eyes ♪</i>

989
01:09:18,201 --> 01:09:22,392
<i>♪ We're so far away from yesterday ♪</i>

990
01:09:22,482 --> 01:09:29,163
<i>♪ Together with a wink and a smile ♪</i>

991
01:09:31,241 --> 01:09:34,570
<i>♪ We go together ♪</i>

992
01:09:34,893 --> 01:09:39,882
<i>♪ Like a wink and a smile ♪♪</i>

993
01:09:48,841 --> 01:09:51,372
<i>I watched him play with
his son at the beach.</i>

994
01:09:51,476 --> 01:09:53,083
<i>Did you talk to him?</i>

995
01:09:53,665 --> 01:09:55,072
Couldn't do it.

996
01:09:57,697 --> 01:09:59,080
How did I get here?

997
01:09:59,187 --> 01:10:01,147
<i>You told a lie and got on a plane.</i>

998
01:10:01,314 --> 01:10:03,072
That's not what I mean.

999
01:10:04,523 --> 01:10:06,693
I'm going back over
there tomorrow

1000
01:10:06,859 --> 01:10:08,483
and talk to him. I am.

1001
01:10:08,577 --> 01:10:12,323
<i>- Okay. Good. Goodbye.</i>
- Beck.

1002
01:10:12,447 --> 01:10:13,549
<i>What?</i>

1003
01:10:16,159 --> 01:10:20,657
- Is this crazy?
<i>- No, that's the weirdest part about it.</i>

1004
01:10:21,873 --> 01:10:25,529
Thank you. I love you.

1005
01:10:26,302 --> 01:10:27,818
Good night.

1006
01:11:30,690 --> 01:11:34,002
It's so good to see you.
Where's Greg?

1007
01:11:57,883 --> 01:11:58,976
Hello.

1008
01:12:00,677 --> 01:12:01,750
Hello.

1009
01:12:08,643 --> 01:12:12,314
<i>- So then what happened?
- So then I left, obviously.</i>

1010
01:12:13,033 --> 01:12:15,073
You were standing in
the middle of the street?

1011
01:12:15,098 --> 01:12:18,768
You know that dream when you're walking down the
street naked and everyone is looking at you.

1012
01:12:18,986 --> 01:12:20,356
I love that dream.

1013
01:12:20,666 --> 01:12:24,564
That was nothing compared
to this humiliation. Nothing!

1014
01:12:24,589 --> 01:12:27,080
- But he saw you, right?
- He saw me.

1015
01:12:27,173 --> 01:12:30,141
- You were face to face.
- He said hello.

1016
01:12:30,172 --> 01:12:31,773
He said hello.
And what did you say?

1017
01:12:31,866 --> 01:12:35,781
- And all I could say was hello.
- Oh, my God.

1018
01:12:36,921 --> 01:12:42,121
<i>- All I could say was hello.</i>
- It's a sign.

1019
01:12:42,588 --> 01:12:46,979
It's a sign that I have watched
this movie too many times.

1020
01:12:47,901 --> 01:12:51,050
So stupid!
From the minute I listened...

1021
01:12:51,075 --> 01:12:54,797
to that stupid programme on the radio,
I've been a complete jerk.

1022
01:12:54,822 --> 01:12:58,188
- You are not a jerk.
- Thank you. An idiot!

1023
01:12:58,611 --> 01:13:02,921
- You don't know who she was, Annie.
- I saw her. I have a picture of her.

1024
01:13:02,946 --> 01:13:04,595
I'll show you a picture of her.

1025
01:13:04,620 --> 01:13:07,517
That detective in Seattle
sent me a picture of her.

1026
01:13:07,542 --> 01:13:11,224
Here! See, that's exactly
what she looks like.

1027
01:13:11,955 --> 01:13:14,157
This is a picture
of someone's back.

1028
01:13:14,276 --> 01:13:16,775
Well, it's her and he
was crazy about her.

1029
01:13:17,557 --> 01:13:21,091
- What's this?
- This is from Seattle.

1030
01:13:29,221 --> 01:13:30,635
Becky.

1031
01:13:32,914 --> 01:13:34,736
So I mailed your letter.

1032
01:13:37,187 --> 01:13:41,369
"Dear Annie. Thanks for your letter.
It was great.

1033
01:13:41,598 --> 01:13:43,611
You sound neat.

1034
01:13:46,595 --> 01:13:52,329
We're very excited about meeting you in New
York on Valentine's Day and seeing if we are...

1035
01:13:53,103 --> 01:13:55,415
M-F-E-O.

1036
01:13:56,340 --> 01:14:00,345
See you soon.
Sleepless in Seattle."

1037
01:14:00,876 --> 01:14:03,666
M-F-E-O?

1038
01:14:06,649 --> 01:14:08,649
Made for each other.

1039
01:14:10,352 --> 01:14:13,883
It's cute. It's like a little clue.

1040
01:14:18,268 --> 01:14:21,648
So he can't write.
Big deal.

1041
01:14:21,673 --> 01:14:24,735
Verbal ability is a highly
overrated thing in a guy.

1042
01:14:24,760 --> 01:14:27,578
And our pathetic need for it is
what gets us into so much trouble.

1043
01:14:27,603 --> 01:14:31,367
I'm going to run back to Walter's
arms, if he'll still have me.

1044
01:14:31,462 --> 01:14:32,953
What about the letter?

1045
01:14:33,085 --> 01:14:37,078
It's nothing. It was written before
I went out there. Before the ho.

1046
01:14:40,290 --> 01:14:43,670
The only thing is,
she didn't look like a ho.

1047
01:14:43,835 --> 01:14:47,295
She looked like somebody we
would have been friends with.

1048
01:14:48,964 --> 01:14:50,334
Ugh!

1049
01:14:51,328 --> 01:14:53,611
You saw her in the airport
and then here?

1050
01:14:53,636 --> 01:14:56,889
And I tried to talk to her. It was like
I knew her or something. It was weird.

1051
01:14:56,914 --> 01:14:58,515
You mean like a déjà-vu thing?

1052
01:14:58,548 --> 01:15:01,976
It was very French déjà-vu-ish
kind of thing. Oui?

1053
01:15:02,001 --> 01:15:05,461
Oui. At least you're out there seeing
people again. That's terrific.

1054
01:15:06,190 --> 01:15:08,501
Well, I mean, there's
really just the one.

1055
01:15:08,625 --> 01:15:12,530
- Victoria.
- You don't like Victoria?

1056
01:15:12,696 --> 01:15:15,804
- She laughs like a hyena.
- Is this true?

1057
01:15:15,829 --> 01:15:16,992
No!

1058
01:15:17,969 --> 01:15:21,647
Sort of. Yeah, a little bit.
But, tell them what you did.

1059
01:15:21,672 --> 01:15:23,522
- Dad...
- Tell them about the radio show.

1060
01:15:23,547 --> 01:15:24,444
- Go ahead.
- Dad...

1061
01:15:24,469 --> 01:15:25,953
They wanna hear it. Go ahead.
Tell them. Tell them.

1062
01:15:25,978 --> 01:15:29,812
Christmas Eve, he phones in
one of those radio call-in shows.

1063
01:15:29,837 --> 01:15:34,750
- And tells them I need a new wife.
- Oh, you're kidding.

1064
01:15:34,844 --> 01:15:36,523
That's so sweet.

1065
01:15:36,836 --> 01:15:39,803
Now he's obsessed with
this one woman who wrote me.

1066
01:15:39,828 --> 01:15:41,209
- Are you serious?
- Yeah.

1067
01:15:41,234 --> 01:15:43,969
She wants to meet me at the
top of Empire State Building.

1068
01:15:44,062 --> 01:15:46,265
On Valentine's Day.

1069
01:15:46,905 --> 01:15:49,366
- It's like that movie.
- What movie?

1070
01:15:49,459 --> 01:15:52,287
An Affair to Remember.
Did you ever see it?

1071
01:15:52,396 --> 01:15:57,447
Oh, God. Cary Grant and Deborah Kerr.
Is that "Karr" or "Kerr"?

1072
01:15:57,746 --> 01:15:58,840
Kerr.

1073
01:15:59,543 --> 01:16:03,574
Okay. She's gonna meet him at the
top of the Empire State Building.

1074
01:16:03,676 --> 01:16:06,043
Only she got hit by a taxi.

1075
01:16:06,373 --> 01:16:10,973
And he waited and waited.
And it was raining, I think.

1076
01:16:11,571 --> 01:16:17,748
And then she's too proud
to tell him that she's...

1077
01:16:20,553 --> 01:16:25,796
crippled. And he's too proud
to find out why she doesn't come.

1078
01:16:26,593 --> 01:16:30,480
But he comes to see her anyway.
And I forget why, but...

1079
01:16:30,882 --> 01:16:34,119
Oh, it's so amazing
when he comes to see her.

1080
01:16:34,323 --> 01:16:39,604
Because he doesn't even notice
that she doesn't get up to say hello.

1081
01:16:39,831 --> 01:16:42,416
And he's very bitter.

1082
01:16:43,384 --> 01:16:47,673
You think he's just going
to walk out the door...

1083
01:16:47,821 --> 01:16:51,044
and never know why she's
just lying there.

1084
01:16:51,069 --> 01:16:57,063
You know, like on the couch with this
blanket over her shrivelled little legs.

1085
01:16:57,663 --> 01:16:58,593
And...

1086
01:16:58,959 --> 01:17:01,600
- Are you all right?
- She's fine.

1087
01:17:01,763 --> 01:17:05,771
And suddenly, he goes,
"I saw the painting"

1088
01:17:05,864 --> 01:17:08,857
And he, like, goes to the bedroom.

1089
01:17:08,980 --> 01:17:11,512
And he looks, and he comes
out and looks at her.

1090
01:17:11,537 --> 01:17:16,678
And he kind of just...
They know and hug and it's so...

1091
01:17:17,587 --> 01:17:20,889
- That's a chick's movie.
- I would say so.

1092
01:17:21,168 --> 01:17:24,668
What kind of a person would write
to someone they heard on the radio?

1093
01:17:24,693 --> 01:17:27,676
I got hundreds of letters
from women all over the country.

1094
01:17:27,701 --> 01:17:28,871
Desperate women.

1095
01:17:28,948 --> 01:17:32,622
Just because someone is looking for a
nice guy, it doesn't make them desperate.

1096
01:17:32,647 --> 01:17:34,350
How about rapacious
and love-starved?

1097
01:17:34,405 --> 01:17:35,015
No.

1098
01:17:35,101 --> 01:17:37,904
It's easier to be killed by a
terrorist than to find a husband...

1099
01:17:37,929 --> 01:17:40,480
- after the age of 40.
- That is absolutely untrue!

1100
01:17:40,504 --> 01:17:42,507
Right, honey. Right.

1101
01:17:42,925 --> 01:17:44,835
Well, I'm not looking
for a mail-order bride.

1102
01:17:44,860 --> 01:17:49,229
I just want somebody that I can have a
decent conversation with over dinner.

1103
01:17:49,315 --> 01:17:53,719
You know, without it falling down into weepy
tears over some movie that she just saw.

1104
01:17:53,744 --> 01:17:54,696
She's very emotional.

1105
01:17:54,721 --> 01:17:56,412
Although, I cried at the
end of The Dirty Dozen.

1106
01:17:56,437 --> 01:17:58,203
- Well, who didn't?
- Jim Brown was throwing...

1107
01:17:58,228 --> 01:18:00,427
these hand grenades
down these air shafts.

1108
01:18:00,452 --> 01:18:05,232
And Richard Jaeckel and Lee Marvin we sitting
on top of this armoured personnel carrier.

1109
01:18:05,257 --> 01:18:08,136
They were dressed up like Nazis.
And it was...

1110
01:18:08,187 --> 01:18:09,874
Trini Lopez...
Isn't he?

1111
01:18:10,851 --> 01:18:14,404
He busted his neck when they were
parachuting down behind the Nazi lines.

1112
01:18:14,429 --> 01:18:15,239
Stop it!

1113
01:18:15,264 --> 01:18:20,251
Richard Jaeckel, at the beginning, he had
on a shiny helmet, because he was an MP.

1114
01:18:20,330 --> 01:18:24,423
<i>- Please, no more.</i>
- God, I love that movie.

1115
01:18:33,477 --> 01:18:36,376
This is the best movie
I've ever seen in my life.

1116
01:18:36,453 --> 01:18:37,961
What's so great about it?

1117
01:18:38,259 --> 01:18:40,673
You have to find her, Jonah.
You have to go to her.

1118
01:18:40,775 --> 01:18:43,290
Do you know how much money
it costs to go to New York?

1119
01:18:43,376 --> 01:18:47,446
Nobody knows.
It changes practically every day.

1120
01:18:47,758 --> 01:18:49,448
How much money do you have?

1121
01:18:49,621 --> 01:18:50,961
80 dollars.

1122
01:18:51,172 --> 01:18:55,752
- I have 42. That'll probably cover cabs.
- But how would I get there?

1123
01:18:56,589 --> 01:18:59,181
Honey, I have to run these
tickets over to someone.

1124
01:18:59,206 --> 01:19:01,380
Can you keep an eye on things
out front till I get back?

1125
01:19:01,480 --> 01:19:02,599
Sure, Mum.

1126
01:19:13,619 --> 01:19:16,830
You want a window seat or aisle?
Window.

1127
01:19:17,026 --> 01:19:19,939
- You want a fruit plate?
- I don't know. Do I?

1128
01:19:19,963 --> 01:19:21,975
I'd rather die than
eat airplane food.

1129
01:19:22,111 --> 01:19:24,289
I'm telling them you're 12 so
you can fly unaccompanied...

1130
01:19:24,314 --> 01:19:26,696
and the stewardess won't carry
you around and stuff like that.

1131
01:19:26,721 --> 01:19:29,360
Are you crazy?
Who'd believe I'm 12?

1132
01:19:29,501 --> 01:19:32,189
If it's in the computer,
they'll believe anything.

1133
01:19:32,267 --> 01:19:33,790
Are you sure?

1134
01:19:34,241 --> 01:19:36,661
Do you want me to say that you're
really, really short for your age,

1135
01:19:36,694 --> 01:19:39,123
and they shouldn't say anything
